    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-02-18T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-02-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="567"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d567">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/684: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-18T13:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 18, 1919, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received February 19, 2 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Russian Minister states that since the body exercising legal authority over
                    the Chinese Eastern Railway is the Pravlinia [<hi rend="italic">Pravlenie</hi>]
                    or Administrative Board organized 1917 to take the place of Petrograd Governing
                    Board, it should be consulted with respect to proposed international control.
                    Board is composed of six Russians, two Chinese, including Kolchack,<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d567fn11">Admiral Alexander V. Kolchak, Dictator of the all-Russian
                        government at Omsk.</note> Ostrogoff<note n="12" xml:id="d567fn12"
                        >Undoubtedly L. A. Ustrugov, Minister of Ways of Communication in the
                        government at Omsk.</note> and Governor Kuo.<note n="13" xml:id="d567fn13"
                        >Kuo Hsiang-hsi, Civil Governor of Kirin; appointed President of the Chinese
                        Eastern Railway in 1918.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0699" n="597" xml:id="pg_597"/>
                <p>Chinese Minister of Railways stated China willing to accept control international
                    commission but desires administration Chinese Eastern Railway be put in the
                    hands of Chinese experts. I stated that as the proposed arrangement was made on
                    the basis of existing legal rights there would probably be some objection to
                    turning the administration over to the Chinese Government, although employment
                    of Chinese might be favorably thought of.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
